<m0>   WASHINGTON (--) (AP) (--) In summer of 1994, Intuit Inc.'s chief financial officer, William H. Lane III, shared some exciting news with his wife: The company was going to be bought out by Microsoft Corp. At the time, the $2 billion deal would have been the software industry's biggest merger.<ep>
   The problem was, Kathleen Lane shared the secret with her son and daughter. The children, together with three others, used the merger news to buy Intuit stock and options ahead of the Microsoft announcement. And then they bailed out a year later when Mrs. Lane warned them of the merger's imminent collapse, federal regulators said Thursday.<ep>
   Thus evolved one of the more unusual insider trading cases, in which a <m2><ql>
<ql>
